A. Querying (using ANY, ALL, UNION, INTERSECT, JOIN, Constraints etc.) 




A. Querying using ANY, ALL, UNION, INTERSECT, JOIN, Constraints
1. Aim

To perform SQL queries using ANY, ALL, UNION, INTERSECT, JOIN operations and apply constraints.

2. Theory

SQL provides advanced querying features:

ANY / ALL → Compare values from subqueries
UNION / INTERSECT → Combine query results
JOIN → Combine tables
Constraints → Maintain data integrity
3. Program / Procedure
Step 1: Create Tables with Constraints
CREATE TABLE Student (
    RollNo INT PRIMARY KEY,
    Name VARCHAR(30),
    Dept VARCHAR(10)
);

CREATE TABLE Marks (
    RollNo INT,
    Subject VARCHAR(20),
    Marks INT CHECK (Marks BETWEEN 0 AND 100),
    FOREIGN KEY (RollNo) REFERENCES Student(RollNo)
);
Step 2: Insert Data
INSERT INTO Student VALUES (101, 'Ravi', 'CSE');
INSERT INTO Student VALUES (102, 'Anu', 'ECE');
INSERT INTO Student VALUES (103, 'Kiran', 'EEE');

INSERT INTO Marks VALUES (101, 'DBMS', 85);
INSERT INTO Marks VALUES (101, 'OS', 78);
INSERT INTO Marks VALUES (102, 'DBMS', 90);
INSERT INTO Marks VALUES (103, 'OS', 60);
4. Queries
a) JOIN (Inner Join)
SELECT S.Name, M.Subject, M.Marks
FROM Student S
INNER JOIN Marks M
ON S.RollNo = M.RollNo;
b) ANY Operator
SELECT Name
FROM Student
WHERE RollNo = ANY (
    SELECT RollNo FROM Marks WHERE Marks > 80
);
c) ALL Operator
SELECT Name
FROM Student
WHERE RollNo = ALL (
    SELECT RollNo FROM Marks WHERE Marks >= 60
);
d) UNION
SELECT RollNo FROM Student
UNION
SELECT RollNo FROM Marks;
e) INTERSECT
SELECT RollNo FROM Student
INTERSECT
SELECT RollNo FROM Marks;
f) Constraint Check (Example)
INSERT INTO Marks VALUES (104, 'DBMS', 120);  -- Will fail (CHECK constraint)
5. Output (What to Write)
Tables created with constraints
Data inserted successfully
JOIN displays combined data
ANY and ALL return filtered results
UNION and INTERSECT show combined and common data
Constraint prevents invalid data












B. Nested, Correlated subqueries




B. Nested & Correlated Subqueries
1. Aim

To write and execute SQL queries using nested subqueries and correlated subqueries.

2. Theory

A subquery is a query written inside another query.

Nested Subquery → Executes once and passes result to outer query
Correlated Subquery → Executes repeatedly for each row of outer query
3. Program / Procedure
Step 1: Create Tables
CREATE TABLE Student (
    RollNo INT PRIMARY KEY,
    Name VARCHAR(30),
    Dept VARCHAR(10)
);

CREATE TABLE Marks (
    RollNo INT,
    Subject VARCHAR(20),
    Marks INT,
    FOREIGN KEY (RollNo) REFERENCES Student(RollNo)
);
Step 2: Insert Data
INSERT INTO Student VALUES (101, 'Ravi', 'CSE');
INSERT INTO Student VALUES (102, 'Anu', 'ECE');
INSERT INTO Student VALUES (103, 'Kiran', 'EEE');

INSERT INTO Marks VALUES (101, 'DBMS', 85);
INSERT INTO Marks VALUES (101, 'OS', 78);
INSERT INTO Marks VALUES (102, 'DBMS', 92);
INSERT INTO Marks VALUES (103, 'OS', 60);
4. Queries
a) Nested Subquery

Find students who scored more than 80

SELECT Name
FROM Student
WHERE RollNo IN (
    SELECT RollNo FROM Marks WHERE Marks > 80
);
b) Nested Subquery with Aggregate

Find students having marks greater than average

SELECT Name
FROM Student
WHERE RollNo IN (
    SELECT RollNo FROM Marks
    WHERE Marks > (SELECT AVG(Marks) FROM Marks)
);
c) Correlated Subquery

Find students who scored more than 90 in any subject

SELECT Name
FROM Student S
WHERE EXISTS (
    SELECT *
    FROM Marks M
    WHERE S.RollNo = M.RollNo AND M.Marks > 90
);
d) Correlated Subquery with Comparison

Find students whose marks are above their own average

SELECT Name
FROM Student S
WHERE EXISTS (
    SELECT *
    FROM Marks M
    WHERE M.RollNo = S.RollNo
    AND M.Marks > (
        SELECT AVG(Marks)
        FROM Marks
        WHERE RollNo = S.RollNo
    )
);
5. Output (What to Write)
Tables created and data inserted
Nested subqueries executed successfully
Correlated subqueries executed for each row
Correct filtered results obtained
